|WKBHELP - ALIAS
============
|WKOThe |YKB"alias" |WKOcommmand allows you to abbreviate commonly used commands
to make them quicker and simplier to use. The commands usable with
alias are as follows:

|YKBalias list      |WKOsimply shows you all the aliases you currently have
                saved. You may have up to 200 different
                aliases at any given time.

|YKBalias <alias>   |WKOThis displays the setting for alias <alias> from your list
                of valid aliases.

|YKBalias remove <alias>
                |WKOThis removes the alias <alias> from your list of valid
                aliases.

|YKBalias <alias> <command>
                |WKOThis command is how you actually set your alias. Instead
                of trying to give you some fancy explanation, I think it
                would be much easier to just give you some examples.

examples:       |YKB"alias ga get all" |WKOenables you to type in |YKB"ga" (without
                the quotes), and pick up everything that you can hold in
                the room.

                |YKB"alias la look at" |WKOenables you to type in
                |YKB"la <something>" (|WKOagain, without the quotes and the
                <>'s), and you will then look at that object.

                You can set an alias to do multiple things by using the
                |YKB'script' |WKOcommand.  |YKB"alias twon script n,n" |WKOwould move
                you two spaces north. |YKB'help script' |WKOfor more info.
HELP - TALIAS
=============
The |YKB"talias" |WKOcommand stands for 'tell alias.'  It is used to shorten
players names which you use frequently. The syntax is similar to that of
the |YKB"alias" |WKOcommand. This can be used when you are talking to people via
the tell command, and also when you are performing an emotion at someone.
An explanation of the different talias commands follows:

|YKBtalias list     |WKOSimply shows all the taliases you currently have saved.
                You may have up to 200 different taliases
                at any given time.

|YKBtalias <talias> |WKOThis displays the setting for talias <talias> from your list
                of valid taliases.

|YKBtalias remove <talias>
                |WKOThis removes the talias <talias> from your list of valid
                taliases.

|YKBtalias <talias> <person>
                |WKOThis command is how use actually set your talias. Instead
                of trying to give you some fancy explanation, I think it
                would be much easier to just give you some examples.

examples:       |YKB"talias nf nightflyer" |WKOadds a talias for 'nf' to be
                Nightflyer. You may now type |YKB"gwave nf" |WKOinstead of
                |YKB"gwave nightflyer"|WKO, and you will wave in greeting to
                Nightflyer.

                This also works in combination with regular aliases.
                Assume that you have an |YKB"alias t tell" |WKOand a
                |YKB"talias nf nightflyer"|WKO.  Now you can |YKB"t nf Hi."|WKO and
                Nightflyer (assuming he's logged on, of course!) will see
                you say "Hi." to him!

